{
  "text": "For univariable comparisons of characteristics between patients, categorical data were compared by \u03c7 2 test, and continuous variables, which were normally distributed, were compared by t tests. Univariable and multivariable conditional logistic regression was then used to investigate the association between postoperative delirium and storage duration of transfused red cell units. We considered storage duration as a binary variable (exclusively \u226414 vs >14 days and average of all units \u226421 vs >21 days) or as a continuous variable, with a spline term at 14 or 21 days. By using a spline term, we could determine whether the risk of delirium increased with each day of additional storage after a certain cutoff, without considering the effect of storage age before the cutoff. Before data collection, we chose 14 days as a cutoff by using results from published studies. [CITATION_1] We also chose 21 days a priori as a cutoff because of evidence suggesting that storage times longer than 14 days might lead to even more morbidity, [CITATION_2] and to allow comparison of results with the results from the large ongoing, multicenter Red Cell Storage Duration Study (RECESS) that uses a similar storage age cutoff of 21 days. [CITATION_3] The variables included in the final multivariable model either were chosen a priori (age, number of red cell units, cardiopulmonary bypass time, and emergency status) or were considered a priori and also confirmed through forward and backward stepwise selection and Akaike information criteria (cerebrovascular disease). Goodness of fit of the models was examined by using Hosmer and Lemeshow goodness-of-fit tests. Transformations or spline terms for continuous variables were considered for inclusion in the model through visual inspection of graphs of the log odds of delirium. Likelihood ratio testing was used to determine the contribution of transformations or spline terms, with the result that the simplest model assuming a linear relationship was chosen. The potential effect of number of red cell units, patient age, and history of cerebrovascular disease on the association between length of red cell unit storage and delirium were all investigated by using interaction terms in multivariable conditional logistic regression models, using the same variables included in the final model.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "8687331",
    "[CITATION_2]": "25545259",
